<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.culturalorientation.net/kurds/">www.culturalorientation.net/kurds/</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
I wonder if the US had really expected the religious leaders in Iraq to immediately take up the strong leadership role they have.  I know I've heard of some miscellaneous people trying to establish themselves as local leaders, but I don't think anyone has gotten the kind of following the religious guys have. Coming from the (supposedly) SOCAS background our leaders have, I wonder how well they'll be able to deal with that.<br>
<br>
Kate <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#9fb7df><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> sweetpeas mommy</span><br> <span class=usertitle>Unregistered User</span><br>   <font color=#3333ff>(4/22/03 10:37 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=194.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: The Kurds</span><hr size=1> Kate, that web link was really interesting! AND good for my late night mommy brain since the explanations on each section were short and concise. LOL.<br>
<br>
&quot;Coming from the (supposedly) SOCAS background our leaders have, I wonder how well they'll be able to deal with that.&quot;<br>
<br>
That was one of the things that I was thinking about when I was reading that study on the Kurds. In the cultural section, it discussed how Americans might do things that in Kurdish culture would send the totally wrong message. I think a lot of our leaders never thought about how to deal with this in an Iraqi mindset and thought only in terms of American values and standards. Personally, I wonder how they will react when they realize their mistake. (Assuming they do realize it, LOL)<br>
<br>
